The *Outline view *visualises the document structure.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAPCAYAAADtc08vAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAX0lEQVQokWNwcHD4////fwZysIODw38mBgrBcDTAYuWd/+hsi5V3/sMwUS7ApvBEuArjiXAVRqIMOBGuwohuCEkugBlCyHYGBgYGFlwGoNuOU3I0JTIwOjg44A4gIgAAjWp/c/m7zecAAAAASUVORK5CYII=) Namespaces
The *Namespaces *node displays the XML namespaces used for a document. In order to add further *Namespaces *to a document simply add a *Namespace *element from the Palette (See chapter ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Namespace](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1#namespace)).

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Page Masters
*Page Master *concept is taken from the XSL-FO specification and is used to define the size and shape of a page and its extensions. For common use a so called *Simple Page Master *is used for one *Page Sequence*. Using *Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Layout &gt; master-reference *the reference to the chosen *Page Master *can be set. By default this is the predefined *A4 Page Master*.

The *Page Masters *dialog can be opened by double clicking a *Page Master *instance in the *Page Masters *node in the *Outline view*. The dialog that opens allows specifying many dimension of the actual document. A preview window in the dialog shows the settings and their modifications while configuring a *Page Master*. To get a feeling for the use of *Page Masters *it might be the easiest to play around a little and to watch how changes of the certain values affect the PDF preview.

Besides, the underlying concept allows creation of complex page layout settings using a simple user interface. That is, application of different page settings for even and odd pages, single and double sided layout, different first or last pages, certain page settings for certain number of pages, etc.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 152. Page Masters*

The subsequent chapters explain the sections of the *Page Master *configuration-dialog.

### Page Dimensions
The *Page Dimension *controls the size of the whole page. A large amount of predefined page formats is listed in the *Format *combo-box. In order to edit properties to custom needs the values in the fields can be altered.

### Page Margins
The *Page Margins *define the distance from the documents physical border defined in the *Page Dimensions *to the printable area. The printable area contains all regions of the document, namely *body*, *top*, *bottom*, *left *and *right*.

### Body Margins
*Body Margins *contain the distances of the *Document Body *to the border defined in the *Page Margins*.

### Extents &amp; Precedence
*Extents *contains the distances of the four regions other than *document body *to the border defined in the *Page Margins*. Using the *top *and *bottom *fields it is possible to adjust the size of the *header *and the *footer*, as well as for *left *and *right*. By entering a value higher than in the corresponding side’s value of the *Body Margin *it is possible to simulate layers within a document, e.g. to enter an *Image *as a background into a *Static Page Content *element, which fills a region bigger than the actual document body.

The *Precedence *options are easiest to understand if once checked and observed in the preview aside. By default the *left *and *right *areas start on top of the page area, so if there are *header*, *footer *and *left*, *right *regions defined there will be the *left *and *right *element “embracing” the *header *and the *footer*. By checking *Precedence *top, the header consumes the whole space from the left to right while having *left*, *body *and *right *below. Same is for the *Precedence *bottom option and the *footer*.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 153. Page Masters: Extents and precedence*

The figure above shows *Page Master *Settings in which *Precedence *top has been chosen. As explained before the *header *region takes all the space from the left to the right and the *footer *region is embraced by the left and right areas, because *Precedence *bottom is not selected.

### Region names
The *Region *names are necessary for assigning the regions of a document:

- header

- footer

- left

- right

- body

Most commonly these regions might be used as document body, respectively header and footer. If these names are changed, the reference in the *Static Page Content *element filling the given area must be set to the right name.

### Complex Page Master
By click on the arrow symbol &gt; on the right-hand side of the configuration-dialog, the added section to define *Complex Page Masters *is shown or hidden. A Complex Page Master contains references to one or more already existing page master definitions.

The first step is to define a name for the new Complex Page Master. Next, existing page masters are inserted with drag&amp;drop from the list in the upper left area to the preview in the lower right corner. In this way references to these page masters are inserted. The preview always displays double sided page masters, but this is irrelevant for the definition. When a reference should be deleted, this can be done by right-click on the element via choosing the option “Delete”.

Finally, the iteration must be specified. This defines how many pages of a document can maximally be rendered with a specific page master reference. The definition is set in the preview in the small input area next to the page master reference. Only one reference can be set to the keyword ‚iterate’, otherwise the definition is invalid and cannot be saved (error message). For all other references a fixed number must be entered.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 154. Complex Page Master*

The figure above shows the definition of a Complex Page Master which references the page masters *Letter_1 *and *Letter_ff*. The example shows a set-up where *Letter_1 *is used to produce the first page of a document, for further pages *Letter_ff *applies.

In case regions should contain different content – for example the first page has a header but not following pages – this must be indicated by different region names. Therefore, page master *Letter_1 *has the name *header_1 *for the top region. Page master *Letter_ff *requires a different name for the top region like *header_ff *to be distinguishable.

If the region names are identical, the same content is shown for all pages of the document, only the exact position may change with the page master.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Bookmarks
![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 155. Bookmarks in a PDF document*

With bookmarks, important points can be highlighted in a PDF document.

### Set references in the document
Before the bookmarks can be defined, the reference points must be defined in the document. Therefore a desired (unique!) ID must be assigned at block level.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 156. Set ID*

After *Set ID *was chosen, the required ID can be entered directly at the block. Once you are finished typing the ID, confirm with the ENTER key.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 157. Set ID on the block*

With *Show ID *the assigned IDs are displayed and can be checked easily

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 158. Show ID*

### Definition of bookmarks
After the IDs are assigned, the bookmarks can be created in the *Outline view*. Sub-groupings are possible as well.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 159. Bookmarks in the Outline View*

The text of the bookmark is set through *Properties*. Furthermore, the ID must be registered as a reference, which is going to be associated with the bookmark. The default value {generate- id()} must therefore be overridden in any case with a valid ID, so that the bookmark works correctly.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 160. link ID as a reference with a Bookmark*

> Note

Attributes for the colour, bold and italic are not supported by all renderers and document readers. Through the Starting state is defined, whether the underlying bookmarks are shown or hidden.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAPCAYAAADtc08vAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAbElEQVQokaWTQQ7AIAgEoenD2JfzNDzZNLoKtnsVxgmomlm4u4qIAAgh6edjAMRNisci1vtkArCmbsZMKODEZAmommwBFZMrA2SZANnUtwB319XOywanJhRwYpJu4dNLfJtkF/xeo5oZ/YHVNGglK66u5aJTAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) Page Sequences, Page Sequence &amp; Page Content
The structure of *Page Sequences *containing *Page Sequence *elements is taken from the XSL- FO standard. This structure is useful to set attributes to different content levels and of course to your own content.

In order to create a plain *Infinica *template it is not necessary to worry about these issues, as the structure is created out of the box with default settings. Additional adjustments might just be necessary for experts in order to match their needs.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,) Template Parts
*Template Parts *are a powerful concept of reusable components. The *Template Parts *node in the *Outline *view contains all local *Template Parts*, i.e. document components reusable within the containing template.

## ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAkAAAAJCAYAAADgkQYQAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAcklEQVQYlXXNQRGDMBSE4T/QOxw5RgISNk6KgzpCAw7ioJUQCaDg9ZIyKSR7ejvzzVtHjqQVeFJJ/ztSSpv33gPzFXWX/gL2JpI0ABEYq6gA5dT5sW+AT+4TMD8aQDHGA1gk4cyMEIJVwH/MDEnvPH3LF5cKIzX9/jIyAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) External Resources
Various *Infinica *component types are summed up as External Resources. These *Infinica *components – e.g. *Styles*, *Template Parts *or *Page Masters *– can be collected to packages for reusing and easy maintaining purposes. The *External Resources *node in the *Outline View *is the place in a template where these external packages can be imported.

Using the context menu and choosing *Add Infinica Template *and selecting the *Infinica *resource to be inserted by entering the source path, the resource is imported. Another way to add the reference is to drag an *Infinica Template *element from the *Palette *to the *External Resources *node and input the source name and path either e.g. using *Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Miscellaneous &gt; src*.
